.SH "NAME"
"perlcritic" \- Command\-line interface to critique Perl source.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 10
\&  perlcritic [\-12345 | \-\-brutal | \-\-cruel | \-\-harsh | \-\-stern | \-\-gentle]
\&             [\-\-severity number | name] [{\-p | \-\-profile} file | \-\-noprofile]
\&             [\-\-top [ number ]] [\-\-theme expression] [\-\-include pattern]
\&             [\-\-exclude pattern] [{\-s | \-\-single\-policy} pattern]
\&             [\-\-only | \-\-noonly] [\-\-profile\-strictness {warn|fatal|quiet}]
\&             [\-\-force | \-\-noforce] [\-\-statistics] [\-\-statistics\-only]
\&             [\-\-count | \-C] [\-\-verbose {number | format}] [\-\-allow\-unsafe]
\&             [\-\-color | \-\-nocolor] [\-\-pager pager] [\-\-quiet]
\&             [\-\-color\-severity\-highest color_specification]
\&             [\-\-color\-severity\-high color_specification]
\&             [\-\-color\-severity\-medium color_specification]
\&             [\-\-color\-severity\-low color_specification]
\&             [\-\-color\-severity\-lowest color_specification]
\&             [\-\-files\-with\-violations | \-l]
\&             [\-\-files\-without\-violations | \-L]
\&             [\-\-program\-extensions file_name_extension]
\&             {FILE | DIRECTORY | STDIN}
\&
\&  perlcritic \-\-profile\-proto
\&
\&  perlcritic { \-\-list | \-\-list\-enabled | \-\-list\-themes | \-\-doc pattern [...] }
\&
\&  perlcritic { \-\-help | \-\-options | \-\-man | \-\-version }
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR is a Perl source code analyzer.  It is the executable
front-end to the Perl::Critic engine, which attempts
to identify awkward, hard to read, error-prone, or unconventional
constructs in your code.  Most of the rules are based on Damian
Conway's book \fBPerl Best Practices\fR.  However, \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR is
\&\fBnot\fR limited to enforcing \s-1PBP\s0, and it will even support rules that
contradict Conway.  All rules can easily be configured or disabled to
your liking.
.PP
This documentation only covers how to drive this command.  For all
other information, including how to persistently configure this
command so that you don't have to say so much on the command-line, see
the documentation for Perl::Critic itself.
.SH "USAGE EXAMPLES"
.IX Header "USAGE EXAMPLES"
Before getting into all the gory details, here are some basic usage
examples to help get you started.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    # Report only most severe violations (severity = 5)
\&    perlcritic YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Same as above, but read input from STDIN
\&    perlcritic
\&
\&    # Recursively process all Perl files beneath directory
\&    perlcritic /some/directory
\&
\&    # Report slightly less severe violations too (severity >= 4)
\&    perlcritic \-4 YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Same as above, but using named severity level
\&    perlcritic \-\-stern YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Report all violations, regardless of severity (severity >= 1)
\&    perlcritic \-1 YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Same as above, but using named severity level
\&    perlcritic \-\-brutal YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Report only violations of things from "Perl Best Practices"
\&    perlcritic \-\-theme pbp YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Report top 20 most severe violations (severity >= 1)
\&    perlcritic \-\-top YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Report additional violations of Policies that match m/variables/xms
\&    perlcritic \-\-include variables YourModule.pm
\&
\&    # Use defaults from somewhere other than ~/.perlcriticrc
\&    perlcriticrc \-\-profile project/specific/perlcriticrc YourModule.pm
.Ve
.SH "ARGUMENTS"
.IX Header "ARGUMENTS"
The arguments are paths to the files you wish to analyze.  You may
specify multiple files.  If an argument is a directory, \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR
will analyze all Perl files below the directory.  If no arguments are
specified, then input is read from \s-1STDIN\s0.
.SH "OPTIONS"
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
Option names can be abbreviated to uniqueness and can be stated with
singe or double dashes, and option values can be separated from the
option name by a space or '=' (as with Getopt::Long).
Option names are also case-sensitive.
.ie n .IP """\-\-profile FILE"" or ""\-p FILE""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-profile FILE\fR or \f(CW\-p FILE\fR" 4
.IX Item "--profile FILE or -p FILE"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to use a profile named by \s-1FILE\s0 rather than
looking for the default \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file in the current directory
or your home directory.  See \*(L"\s-1CONFIGURATION\s0\*(R" in Perl::Critic for more
information.
.ie n .IP """\-\-noprofile""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-noprofile\fR" 4
.IX Item "--noprofile"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR not to load any configuration file, thus
reverting to the default configuration for all Policies.
.ie n .IP """\-\-severity N""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-severity N\fR" 4
.IX Item "--severity N"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to only apply Policies with a severity greater
than \f(CW\*(C`N\*(C'\fR.  Severity values are integers ranging from 1 (least severe)
to 5 (most severe).  The default is 5.  For a given \f(CW\*(C`\-\-profile\*(C'\fR,
decreasing the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR will usually produce more violations.
You can set the default value for this option in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR
file.  You can also redefine the \f(CW\*(C`severity\*(C'\fR for any Policy in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.  See \*(L"\s-1CONFIGURATION\s0\*(R" for more information.
.ie n .IP """\-5 | \-4 | \-3 | \-2 | \-1""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-5 | \-4 | \-3 | \-2 | \-1\fR" 4
.IX Item "-5 | -4 | -3 | -2 | -1"
These are numeric shortcuts for setting the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR option.  For
example, \f(CW"\-4"\fR is equivalent to \f(CW"\-\-severity 4"\fR.  If multiple
shortcuts are specified, then the most restrictive one wins.  If an
explicit \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR option is also given, then all shortcut options
are silently ignored.  \s-1NOTE:\s0 Be careful not to put one of the number
severity shortcut options immediately after the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-top\*(C'\fR flag or
\&\f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR will interpret it as the number of violations to report.
.ie n .IP """\-\-severity NAME""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-severity NAME\fR" 4
.IX Item "--severity NAME"
If it is difficult for you to remember whether severity \*(L"5\*(R" is the
most or least restrictive level, then you can use one of these named
values:
.Sp
.Vb 7
\&    SEVERITY NAME   ...is equivalent to...   SEVERITY NUMBER
\&    \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    \-\-severity gentle                           \-\-severity 5
\&    \-\-severity stern                            \-\-severity 4
\&    \-\-severity harsh                            \-\-severity 3
\&    \-\-severity cruel                            \-\-severity 2
\&    \-\-severity brutal                           \-\-severity 1
.Ve
.ie n .IP """\-\-gentle | \-\-stern | \-\-harsh | \-\-cruel | \-\-brutal""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-gentle | \-\-stern | \-\-harsh | \-\-cruel | \-\-brutal\fR" 4
.IX Item "--gentle | --stern | --harsh | --cruel | --brutal"
These are named shortcuts for setting the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR option.  For
example, \f(CW"\-\-cruel"\fR is equivalent to \f(CW"\-\-severity 2"\fR.  If multiple
shortcuts are specified, then the most restrictive one wins.  If an
explicit \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR option is also given, then all shortcut options
are silently ignored.
.ie n .IP """\-\-theme RULE""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-theme RULE\fR" 4
.IX Item "--theme RULE"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to apply only Policies with themes that satisfy
the \f(CW\*(C`RULE\*(C'\fR.  Themes are arbitrary names for groups of related
policies.  You can combine theme names with boolean operators to
create an arbitrarily complex \f(CW\*(C`RULE\*(C'\fR.  For example, the following
would apply only Policies that have a 'bugs' \s-1AND\s0 'pbp' theme:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    $> perlcritic \-\-theme=\*(Aqbugs && pbp\*(Aq MyModule.pm
.Ve
.Sp
Unless the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR option is explicitly given, setting
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-theme\*(C'\fR silently causes the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR to be set to 1.  You can
set the default value for this option in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
See \*(L"\s-1POLICY\s0 \s-1THEMES\s0\*(R" in Perl::Critic for more information about themes.
.ie n .IP """\-\-include PATTERN""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-include PATTERN\fR" 4
.IX Item "--include PATTERN"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to apply additional Policies that match the
regex \f(CW\*(C`/PATTERN/imx\*(C'\fR.  Use this option to temporarily override your
profile and/or the severity settings at the command-line.  For
example:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    perlcritic \-\-include=layout my_file.pl
.Ve
.Sp
This would cause \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to apply all the \f(CW\*(C`CodeLayout::*\*(C'\fR
policies even if they have a severity level that is less than the
default level of 5, or have been disabled in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR
file.  You can specify multiple \f(CW\*(C`\-\-include\*(C'\fR options and you can use
it in conjunction with the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-exclude\*(C'\fR option.  Note that
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-exclude\*(C'\fR takes precedence over \f(CW\*(C`\-\-include\*(C'\fR when a Policy matches
both patterns.  You can set the default value for this option in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.ie n .IP """\-\-exclude PATTERN""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-exclude PATTERN\fR" 4
.IX Item "--exclude PATTERN"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to not apply any Policy that matches the regex
\&\f(CW\*(C`/PATTERN/imx\*(C'\fR.  Use this option to temporarily override your profile
and/or the severity settings at the command-line.  For example:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    perlcritic \-\-exclude=strict my_file.pl
.Ve
.Sp
This would cause \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to not apply the \f(CW\*(C`RequireUseStrict\*(C'\fR
and \f(CW\*(C`ProhibitNoStrict\*(C'\fR Policies even though they have the highest
severity level.  You can specify multiple \f(CW\*(C`\-\-exclude\*(C'\fR options and you
can use it in conjunction with the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-include\*(C'\fR option.  Note that
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-exclude\*(C'\fR takes precedence over \f(CW\*(C`\-\-include\*(C'\fR when a Policy matches
both patterns.  You can set the default value for this option in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.ie n .IP """\-\-single\-policy PATTERN"" or ""\-s PATTERN""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-single\-policy PATTERN\fR or \f(CW\-s PATTERN\fR" 4
.IX Item "--single-policy PATTERN or -s PATTERN"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to apply just one Policy module matching the
regex \f(CW\*(C`/PATTERN/ixms\*(C'\fR, and exclude all other Policies.  This option
has precedence over the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-theme\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-include\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-exclude\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`\-\-only\*(C'\fR options.  For example:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    perlcritic \-\-single\-policy=nowarnings my_file.pl
.Ve
.Sp
This would cause \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to apply just the \f(CW\*(C`ProhibitNoWarnings\*(C'\fR
Policy, regardless of the severity level setting.  No other Policies
would be applied.
.Sp
This is equivalent to what one might intend by...
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    perlcritic \-\-exclude=. \-\-include=nowarnings my_file.pl
.Ve
.Sp
\&... but this won't work because the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-exclude\*(C'\fR option overrides the
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-include\*(C'\fR option.
.Sp
The equivalent of this option can be accomplished by creating a custom
profile containing only the desired policy and then running...
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    perlcritic \-\-profile=customprofile \-\-only my_file.pl
.Ve
.ie n .IP """\-\-top [ N ]""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-top [ N ]\fR" 4
.IX Item "--top [ N ]"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to report only the top \f(CW\*(C`N\*(C'\fR Policy violations in
each file, ranked by their severity.  If \f(CW\*(C`N\*(C'\fR is not specified, it
defaults to 20.  If the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR option (or one of the shortcuts)
is not explicitly given, the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-top\*(C'\fR option implies that the minimum
severity level is \*(L"1\*(R" (i.e. \*(L"brutal\*(R"). Users can redefine the severity
for any Policy in their \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.  See \*(L"\s-1CONFIGURATION\s0\*(R"
for more information.  You can set the default value for this option
in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.  \s-1NOTE:\s0 Be careful not to put one of the
severity shortcut options immediately after the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-top\*(C'\fR flag or
\&\f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR will interpret it as the number of violations to report.
.ie n .IP """\-\-force""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-force\fR" 4
.IX Item "--force"
Directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to ignore the magical \f(CW"## no critic"\fR
annotations in the source code. See \*(L"\s-1BENDING\s0 \s-1THE\s0 \s-1RULES\s0\*(R" for more
information.  You can set the default value for this option in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.ie n .IP """\-\-statistics""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-statistics\fR" 4
.IX Item "--statistics"
Causes several statistics about the code being scanned and the
violations found to be reported after any other output.
.ie n .IP """\-\-statistics\-only""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-statistics\-only\fR" 4
.IX Item "--statistics-only"
Like the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-statistics\*(C'\fR option, but suppresses normal output and only
shows the statistics.
.ie n .IP """\-\-verbose N | FORMAT""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-verbose N | FORMAT\fR" 4
.IX Item "--verbose N | FORMAT"
Sets the verbosity level or format for reporting violations.  If given
a number (\f(CW\*(C`N\*(C'\fR), \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR reports violations using one of the
predefined formats described below.  If given a string (\f(CW\*(C`FORMAT\*(C'\fR), it
is interpreted to be an actual format specification.  If the
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-verbose\*(C'\fR option is not specified, it defaults to either 4 or 5,
depending on whether multiple files were given as arguments to
\&\f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR.  You can set the default value for this option in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.Sp
.Vb 10
\&    Verbosity     Format Specification
\&    \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-   \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&     1            "%f:%l:%c:%m\en",
\&     2            "%f: (%l:%c) %m\en",
\&     3            "%m at %f line %l\en",
\&     4            "%m at line %l, column %c.  %e.  (Severity: %s)\en",
\&     5            "%f: %m at line %l, column %c.  %e.  (Severity: %s)\en",
\&     6            "%m at line %l, near \*(Aq%r\*(Aq.  (Severity: %s)\en",
\&     7            "%f: %m at line %l near \*(Aq%r\*(Aq.  (Severity: %s)\en",
\&     8            "[%p] %m at line %l, column %c.  (Severity: %s)\en",
\&     9            "[%p] %m at line %l, near \*(Aq%r\*(Aq.  (Severity: %s)\en",
\&    10            "%m at line %l, column %c.\en  %p (Severity: %s)\en%d\en",
\&    11            "%m at line %l, near \*(Aq%r\*(Aq.\en  %p (Severity: %s)\en%d\en"
.Ve
.Sp
Formats are a combination of literal and escape characters similar to
the way \f(CW\*(C`sprintf\*(C'\fR works.  See String::Format for a
full explanation of the formatting capabilities.  Valid escape
characters are:
.Sp
.Vb 10
\&    Escape    Meaning
\&    \-\-\-\-\-\-\-   \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    %c        Column number where the violation occurred
\&    %d        Full diagnostic discussion of the violation
\&    %e        Explanation of violation or page numbers in PBP
\&    %F        Just the name of the file where the violation occurred.
\&    %f        Path to the file where the violation occurred.
\&    %l        Line number where the violation occurred
\&    %m        Brief description of the violation
\&    %P        Full name of the Policy module that created the violation
\&    %p        Name of the Policy without the Perl::Critic::Policy:: prefix
\&    %r        The string of source code that caused the violation
\&    %C        The class of the PPI::Element that caused the violation
\&    %s        The severity level of the violation
.Ve
.Sp
The purpose of these formats is to provide some compatibility with
text editors that have an interface for parsing certain kinds of
input. See \*(L"\s-1EDITOR\s0 \s-1INTEGRATION\s0\*(R" for more information about that.
.ie n .IP """\-\-list""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-list\fR" 4
.IX Item "--list"
Displays a condensed listing of all the
Perl::Critic::Policy modules that are found on this
machine.  This option lists \fIall\fR Policies, regardless of your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR or command line options.  For each Policy, the name, default
severity and default themes are shown.
.ie n .IP """\-\-list\-enabled""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-list\-enabled\fR" 4
.IX Item "--list-enabled"
Displays a condensed listing of all the
Perl::Critic::Policy modules that \fIwould\fR be
enforced, if you were actually going to critique a file with this command.
This is useful when you've constructed a complicated command or modified your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file and you want to see exactly which Policies are going to
be enforced (or not enforced, as the case may be). For each Policy, the name,
default severity and default themes are shown.
.ie n .IP """\-\-list\-themes""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-list\-themes\fR" 4
.IX Item "--list-themes"
Displays a list of all the themes of the
Perl::Critic::Policy modules that are found on
this machine.
.ie n .IP """\-\-profile\-proto""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-profile\-proto\fR" 4
.IX Item "--profile-proto"
Displays an expanded listing of all the
Perl::Critic::Policy modules that are found on
this machine.  For each Policy, the name, default severity and default
themes are shown, as well as the name of any additional parameters
that the Policy supports.  The format is suitable as a prototype for
your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.ie n .IP """\-\-only""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-only\fR" 4
.IX Item "--only"
Directs perlcritic to apply only Policies that are explicitly
mentioned in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.  This is useful if you want
to use just a small subset of Policies without having to disable all
the others.  You can set the default value for this option in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.ie n .IP """\-\-profile\-strictness {warn|fatal|quiet}""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-profile\-strictness {warn|fatal|quiet}\fR" 4
.IX Item "--profile-strictness {warn|fatal|quiet}"
Directs perlcritic how to treat certain recoverable problems found in
a \fI.perlcriticrc\fR or file specified via the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-profile\*(C'\fR option.
Valid values are \f(CW\*(C`warn\*(C'\fR (the default), \f(CW\*(C`fatal\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`quiet\*(C'\fR.  For
example, perlcritic normally only warns about profiles referring to
non-existent Policies, but this option can make this situation fatal.
You can set the default value for this option in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR
file.
.ie n .IP """\-\-count""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-count\fR" 4
.IX Item "--count"
.PD 0
.ie n .IP """\-C""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-C\fR" 4
.IX Item "-C"
.PD
Display only the number of violations for each file.  Use this feature
to get a quick handle on where a large pile of code might need the
most attention.
.ie n .IP """\-\-Safari""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-Safari\fR" 4
.IX Item "--Safari"
Report \*(L"Perl Best Practice\*(R" citations as section numbers from
<http://safari.oreilly.com> instead of page numbers from the actual
book.  \s-1NOTE:\s0 This feature is not implemented yet.
.ie n .IP """\-\-color""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-color\fR" 4
.IX Item "--color"
This option is on when outputting to a tty.  When set, Severity 5 and 4 are
colored red and yellow, respectively.  Colorization only happens if
Term::ANSIColor is installed and it only works on
non-Windows environments.  Negate this switch to disable color.  You can set
the default value for this option in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.Sp
Can also be specified as \f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-pager PAGER_COMMAND_STRING""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-pager PAGER_COMMAND_STRING\fR" 4
.IX Item "--pager PAGER_COMMAND_STRING"
If set, perlcritic will pipe it's output to the given \s-1PAGER_COMMAND_STRING\s0.
You can set the default value for this option in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.
.Sp
Setting a pager turns off color by default.  You will have to turn color on
explicitly.  If you want color, you'll probably also want to tell your pager
to display raw characters.  For \f(CW\*(C`less\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`more\*(C'\fR, use the \-R switch.
.ie n .IP """\-\-color\-severity\-highest COLOR_SPECIFICATION""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-color\-severity\-highest COLOR_SPECIFICATION\fR" 4
.IX Item "--color-severity-highest COLOR_SPECIFICATION"
Specifies the color to be used for highest severity violations, as a
Term::ANSIColor color specification. Can also be specified as
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-highest\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-color\-severity\-5\*(C'\fR, or
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-5\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-color\-severity\-high COLOR_SPECIFICATION""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-color\-severity\-high COLOR_SPECIFICATION\fR" 4
.IX Item "--color-severity-high COLOR_SPECIFICATION"
Specifies the color to be used for high severity violations, as a
Term::ANSIColor color specification. Can also be specified as
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-high\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-color\-severity\-4\*(C'\fR, or
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-4\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-color\-severity\-medium COLOR_SPECIFICATION""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-color\-severity\-medium COLOR_SPECIFICATION\fR" 4
.IX Item "--color-severity-medium COLOR_SPECIFICATION"
Specifies the color to be used for medium severity violations, as a
Term::ANSIColor color specification. Can also be specified as
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-medium\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-color\-severity\-3\*(C'\fR, or
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-3\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-color\-severity\-low COLOR_SPECIFICATION""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-color\-severity\-low COLOR_SPECIFICATION\fR" 4
.IX Item "--color-severity-low COLOR_SPECIFICATION"
Specifies the color to be used for low severity violations, as a
Term::ANSIColor color specification. Can also be specified as
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-low\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-color\-severity\-2\*(C'\fR, or
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-2\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-color\-severity\-lowest COLOR_SPECIFICATION""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-color\-severity\-lowest COLOR_SPECIFICATION\fR" 4
.IX Item "--color-severity-lowest COLOR_SPECIFICATION"
Specifies the color to be used for lowest severity violations, as a
Term::ANSIColor color specification. Can also be specified as
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-lowest\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`\-\-color\-severity\-1\*(C'\fR, or
\&\f(CW\*(C`\-\-colour\-severity\-1\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-files\-with\-violations""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-files\-with\-violations\fR" 4
.IX Item "--files-with-violations"
Display only the names of files with violations.  Use this feature
with \-\-single\-policy to find files that contain violations of a given
policy. Can also be specified as \f(CW\*(C`\-\-l\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-files\-without\-violations""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-files\-without\-violations\fR" 4
.IX Item "--files-without-violations"
Display only the names of files without violations.  Use this feature
with \-\-single\-policy to find files that do not contain violations of a
given policy. Can also be specified as \f(CW\*(C`\-\-L\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-program\-extensions file_name_extension""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-program\-extensions file_name_extension\fR" 4
.IX Item "--program-extensions file_name_extension"
Tell \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to treat files whose names end in the given file name
extension as programs, not as modules. If a leading '.' is desired it must be
explicitly specified, e.g.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    \-\-program\-extensions .pl
.Ve
.Sp
The matching is case-sensitive, and the option may be specified as many times
as desired, e.g.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    \-\-program\-extensions .pl \-\-program\-extensions .cgi
.Ve
.Sp
The above can also be done by quoting the file name extensions:
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    \-\-program\-extensions \*(Aq.pl .cgi\*(Aq
.Ve
.Sp
Files whose name ends in '.PL' will always be considered programs.
.ie n .IP """\-\-doc PATTERN""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-doc PATTERN\fR" 4
.IX Item "--doc PATTERN"
Displays the perldoc for all
Perl::Critic::Policy modules that match
\&\f(CW\*(C`m/PATTERN/ixms\*(C'\fR.  Since Policy modules tend to have rather long
names, this just provides a more convenient way to say something like:
\&\f(CW"perldoc Perl::Critic::Policy::ValuesAndExpressions::RequireUpperCaseHeredocTerminator"\fR
at the command prompt.
.ie n .IP """\-\-allow\-unsafe""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-allow\-unsafe\fR" 4
.IX Item "--allow-unsafe"
This option directs \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR to allow the use of Policies that have been
marked as \*(L"unsafe\*(R".  Unsafe Policies may result in risky operations by
compiling and executing the code they analyze.  All the Policies that ship in
the core Perl::Critic distribution are safe.  However,
third-party Policies, such as those in the
Perl::Critic::Dynamic distribution are not safe.
Note that \*(L"safety\*(R" is honorary \*(-- if a Policy author marks a Policy as safe,
it is not a guarantee that it won't do nasty things.  \fBIf you don't trust
your Policies and the code you are analyzing, then do not use this switch\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-quiet""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-quiet\fR" 4
.IX Item "--quiet"
Suppress the \*(L"source \s-1OK\s0\*(R" message when no violations are found.
.ie n .IP """\-\-help""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-help\fR" 4
.IX Item "--help"
.PD 0
.ie n .IP """\-?""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-?\fR" 4
.IX Item "-?"
.ie n .IP """\-H""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-H\fR" 4
.IX Item "-H"
.PD
Displays a brief summary of options and exits.
.ie n .IP """\-\-options""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-options\fR" 4
.IX Item "--options"
Displays the descriptions of the options and exits.  While this output
is long, it it nowhere near the length of the output of \f(CW\*(C`\-\-man\*(C'\fR.
.ie n .IP """\-\-man""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-man\fR" 4
.IX Item "--man"
Displays the complete \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR manual and exits.
.ie n .IP """\-\-version""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-\-version\fR" 4
.IX Item "--version"
.PD 0
.ie n .IP """\-V""" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW\-V\fR" 4
.IX Item "-V"
.PD
Displays the version number of \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR and exits.
.SH "CONFIGURATION"
.IX Header "CONFIGURATION"
Most of the settings for Perl::Critic and each of the Policy modules
can be controlled by a configuration file.  The default configuration
file is called \fI.perlcriticrc\fR.  \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR will look for this
file in the current directory first, and then in your home directory.
Alternatively, you can set the \f(CW\*(C`PERLCRITIC\*(C'\fR environment variable to
explicitly point to a different file in another location.  If none of
these files exist, and the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-profile\*(C'\fR option is not given on the
command-line, then all Policies will be loaded with their default
configuration.
.PP
The format of the configuration file is a series of INI-style blocks
that contain key-value pairs separated by \*(L"=\*(R". Comments should start
with \*(L"#\*(R" and can be placed on a separate line or after the name-value
pairs if you desire.
.PP
Default settings for perlcritic itself can be set \fBbefore the first
named block.\fR For example, putting any or all of these at the top of
your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file will set the default value for the
corresponding command-line argument.
.PP
.Vb 8
\&    severity  = 3                                     #Integer or named level
\&    only      = 1                                     #Zero or One
\&    force     = 0                                     #Zero or One
\&    verbose   = 4                                     #Integer or format spec
\&    top       = 50                                    #A positive integer
\&    theme     = (pbp + security) * bugs               #A theme expression
\&    include   = NamingConventions ClassHierarchies    #Space\-delimited list
\&    exclude   = Variables  Modules::RequirePackage    #Space\-delimited list
.Ve
.PP
The remainder of the configuration file is a series of blocks like this:
.PP
.Vb 6
\&    [Perl::Critic::Policy::Category::PolicyName]
\&    severity = 1
\&    set_themes = foo bar
\&    add_themes = baz
\&    arg1 = value1
\&    arg2 = value2
.Ve
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`Perl::Critic::Policy::Category::PolicyName\*(C'\fR is the full name of a
module that implements the policy.  The Policy modules distributed
with Perl::Critic have been grouped into categories according to the
table of contents in Damian Conway's book \fBPerl Best Practices\fR. For
brevity, you can omit the \f(CW\*(AqPerl::Critic::Policy\*(Aq\fR part of the module
name.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`severity\*(C'\fR is the level of importance you wish to assign to the
Policy.  All Policy modules are defined with a default severity value
ranging from 1 (least severe) to 5 (most severe).  However, you may
disagree with the default severity and choose to give it a higher or
lower severity, based on your own coding philosophy.  You can set the
\&\f(CW\*(C`severity\*(C'\fR to an integer from 1 to 5, or use one of the equivalent
names:
.PP
.Vb 7
\&    SEVERITY NAME ...is equivalent to... SEVERITY NUMBER
\&    \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    gentle                                             5
\&    stern                                              4
\&    harsh                                              3
\&    cruel                                              2
\&    brutal                                             1
.Ve
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`set_themes\*(C'\fR sets the theme for the Policy and overrides its default
theme.  The argument is a string of one or more whitespace-delimited
alphanumeric words.  Themes are case-insensitive.  See \*(L"\s-1POLICY\s0
\&\s-1THEMES\s0\*(R" for more information.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`add_themes\*(C'\fR appends to the default themes for this Policy.  The
argument is a string of one or more whitespace-delimited words.
Themes are case-insensitive.  See \*(L"\s-1POLICY\s0 \s-1THEMES\s0\*(R" for more
information.
.PP
The remaining key-value pairs are configuration parameters that will
be passed into the constructor of that Policy.  The constructors for
most Policy modules do not support arguments, and those that do should
have reasonable defaults.  See the documentation on the appropriate
Policy module for more details.
.PP
Instead of redefining the severity for a given Policy, you can
completely disable a Policy by prepending a '\-' to the name of the
module in your configuration file.  In this manner, the Policy will
never be loaded, regardless of the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-severity\*(C'\fR given on the command
line.
.PP
A simple configuration might look like this:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    #\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    # I think these are really important, so always load them
\&
\&    [TestingAndDebugging::RequireUseStrict]
\&    severity = 5
\&
\&    [TestingAndDebugging::RequireUseWarnings]
\&    severity = 5
\&
\&    #\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    # I think these are less important, so only load when asked
\&
\&    [Variables::ProhibitPackageVars]
\&    severity = 2
\&
\&    [ControlStructures::ProhibitPostfixControls]
\&    allow = if unless  # My custom configuration
\&    severity = cruel   # Same as "severity = 2"
\&
\&    #\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    # Give these policies a custom theme.  I can activate just
\&    # these policies by saying "perlcritic \-\-theme \*(Aqlarry || curly\*(Aq"
\&
\&    [Modules::RequireFilenameMatchesPackage]
\&    add_themes = larry
\&
\&    [TestingAndDebugging::RequireTestLabels]
\&    add_themes = curly moe
\&
\&    #\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    # I do not agree with these at all, so never load them
\&
\&    [\-NamingConventions::Capitalization]
\&    [\-ValuesAndExpressions::ProhibitMagicNumbers]
\&
\&    #\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    # For all other Policies, I accept the default severity,
\&    # so no additional configuration is required for them.
.Ve
.PP
Note that all policies included with the Perl::Critic distribution
that have integer parameters accept underscores (\*(L"_\*(R") in their values,
as with Perl numeric literals.  For example,
.PP
.Vb 2
\&    [ValuesAndExpressions::RequireNumberSeparators]
\&    min_value = 1_000
.Ve
.PP
For additional configuration examples, see the \fIperlcriticrc\fR file
that is included in this \fIexamples\fR directory of this distribution.
.PP
Damian Conway's own Perl::Critic configuration is also included in
this distribution as \fIexamples/perlcriticrc\-conway\fR.
.SH "THE POLICIES"
.IX Header "THE POLICIES"
A large number of Policy modules are distributed with Perl::Critic.
They are described briefly in the companion document
Perl::Critic::PolicySummary and in more
detail in the individual modules themselves.  Say \f(CW"perlcritic \-\-doc
PATTERN"\fR to see the perldoc for all Policy modules that match the
regex \f(CW\*(C`m/PATTERN/ixms\*(C'\fR
.PP
There are a number of distributions of additional policies on \s-1CPAN\s0.
If Perl::Critic doesn't contain a policy that you
want, some one may have already written it.  See \*(L"\s-1SEE\s0
\&\s-1ALSO\s0\*(R" in Perl::Critic for a list of some of these distributions.
.SH "POLICY THEMES"
.IX Header "POLICY THEMES"
Each Policy is defined with one or more \*(L"themes\*(R".  Themes can be used
to create arbitrary groups of Policies.  They are intended to provide
an alternative mechanism for selecting your preferred set of Policies.
For example, you may wish disable a certain set of Policies when
analyzing test programs.  Conversely, you may wish to enable only a
specific subset of Policies when analyzing modules.
.PP
The Policies that ship with Perl::Critic are have been divided into
the following themes.  This is just our attempt to provide some basic
logical groupings.  You are free to invent new themes that suit your
needs.
.PP
.Vb 10
\&    THEME             DESCRIPTION
\&    \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    core              All policies that ship with Perl::Critic
\&    pbp               Policies that come directly from "Perl Best Practices"
\&    bugs              Policies that that prevent or reveal bugs
\&    maintenance       Policies that affect the long\-term health of the code
\&    cosmetic          Policies that only have a superficial effect
\&    complexity        Policies that specificaly relate to code complexity
\&    security          Policies that relate to security issues
\&    tests             Policies that are specific to test programs
.Ve
.PP
Say \f(CW"perlcritic \-\-list"\fR to get a listing of all available policies
and the themes that are associated with each one.  You can also change
the theme for any Policy in your \fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.  See the
\&\*(L"\s-1CONFIGURATION\s0\*(R" section for more information about that.
.PP
Using the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-theme\*(C'\fR command-line option, you can create an
arbitrarily complex rule that determines which Policies to apply.
Precedence is the same as regular Perl code, and you can use
parentheses to enforce precedence as well.  Supported operators are:
.PP
.Vb 5
\&    Operator    Altertative    Example
\&    \-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-\-
\&    &&          and            \*(Aqpbp && core\*(Aq
\&    ||          or             \*(Aqpbp || (bugs && security)\*(Aq
\&    !           not            \*(Aqpbp && ! (portability || complexity)\*(Aq
.Ve
.PP
Theme names are case-insensitive.  If the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-theme\*(C'\fR is set to an
empty string, then it evaluates as true all Policies.
.SH "BENDING THE RULES"
.IX Header "BENDING THE RULES"
Perl::Critic takes a hard-line approach to your code: either you
comply or you don't.  In the real world, it is not always practical
(or even possible) to fully comply with coding standards.  In such
cases, it is wise to show that you are knowingly violating the
standards and that you have a Damn Good Reason (\s-1DGR\s0) for doing so.
.PP
To help with those situations, you can direct Perl::Critic to ignore
certain lines or blocks of code by using annotations:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&  require \*(AqLegacyLibaray1.pl\*(Aq;  ## no critic
\&  require \*(AqLegacyLibrary2.pl\*(Aq;  ## no critic
\&
\&  for my $element (@list) {
\&
\&      ## no critic
\&
\&      $foo = "";               #Violates \*(AqProhibitEmptyQuotes\*(Aq
\&      $barf = bar() if $foo;   #Violates \*(AqProhibitPostfixControls\*(Aq
\&      #Some more evil code...
\&
\&      ## use critic
\&
\&      #Some good code...
\&      do_something($_);
\&  }
.Ve
.PP
The \f(CW"## no critic"\fR annotations direct Perl::Critic to ignore the remaining
lines of code until a \f(CW"## use critic"\fR annotation is found. If the \f(CW"## no
critic"\fR annotation is on the same line as a code statement, then only that
line of code is overlooked.  To direct perlcritic to ignore the \f(CW"## no
critic"\fR annotations, use the \f(CW\*(C`\-\-force\*(C'\fR option.
.PP
A bare \f(CW"## no critic"\fR annotation disables all the active Policies.  If
you wish to disable only specific Policies, add a list of Policy names
as arguments just as you would for the \f(CW"no strict"\fR or \f(CW"no
warnings"\fR pragma.  For example, this would disable the
\&\f(CW\*(C`ProhibitEmptyQuotes\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`ProhibitPostfixControls\*(C'\fR policies until
the end of the block or until the next \f(CW"## use critic"\fR annotation
(whichever comes first):
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    ## no critic (EmptyQuotes, PostfixControls);
\&
\&    # Now exempt from ValuesAndExpressions::ProhibitEmptyQuotes
\&    $foo = "";
\&
\&    # Now exempt ControlStructures::ProhibitPostfixControls
\&    $barf = bar() if $foo;
\&
\&    # Still subject to ValuesAndExpression::RequireNumberSeparators
\&    $long_int = 10000000000;
.Ve
.PP
Since the Policy names are matched against the \f(CW"## no critic"\fR
arguments as regular expressions, you can abbreviate the Policy names
or disable an entire family of Policies in one shot like this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&    ## no critic (NamingConventions)
\&
\&    # Now exempt from NamingConventions::Capitalization
\&    my $camelHumpVar = \*(Aqfoo\*(Aq;
\&
\&    # Now exempt from NamingConventions::Capitalization
\&    sub camelHumpSub {}
.Ve
.PP
The argument list must be enclosed in parentheses and must contain one
or more comma-separated barewords (i.e. don't use quotes).  The \f(CW"##
no critic"\fR annotations can be nested, and Policies named by an inner
annotation will be disabled along with those already disabled an outer
annotation.
.PP
Some Policies like \f(CW\*(C`Subroutines::ProhibitExcessComplexity\*(C'\fR apply to
an entire block of code.  In those cases, \f(CW"## no critic"\fR must
appear on the line where the violation is reported.  For example:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&    sub complicated_function {  ## no critic (ProhibitExcessComplexity)
\&        # Your code here...
\&    }
.Ve
.PP
Some Policies like \f(CW\*(C`Documentation::RequirePodSections\*(C'\fR apply to the
entire document, in which case violations are reported at line 1.  But
if the file requires a shebang line, it is impossible to put \f(CW"## no
critic"\fR on the first line of the file.  This is a known limitation
and it will be addressed in a future release.  As a workaround, you
can disable the affected policies at the command-line or in your
\&\fI.perlcriticrc\fR file.  But beware that this will affect the analysis
of \fBall\fR files.
.PP
Use this feature wisely.  \f(CW"## no critic"\fR should be used in the
smallest possible scope, or only on individual lines of code. And you
should always be as specific as possible about which policies you want
to disable (i.e. never use a bare \f(CW"## no critic"\fR).  If Perl::Critic
complains about your code, try and find a compliant solution before
resorting to this feature.
.SH "EDITOR INTEGRATION"
.IX Header "EDITOR INTEGRATION"
For ease-of-use, \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR can be integrated with your favorite
text editor.  The output-formatting capabilities of \f(CW\*(C`perlcritic\*(C'\fR are
specifically intended for use with the \*(L"grep\*(R" or \*(L"compile\*(R" modes
available in editors like \f(CW\*(C`emacs\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`vim\*(C'\fR.  In these modes, you
can run an arbitrary command and the editor will parse the output into
an interactive buffer that you can click on and jump to the relevant
line of code.
.PP
The Perl::Critic team thanks everyone who has helped integrate Perl-Critic
with their favorite editor.  Your contributions in particular have made
Perl-Critic a convenient and user-friendly tool for Perl developers of all
stripes.  We sincerely appreciate your hard work.
.SS "\s-1EMACS\s0"
